==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in the 1520's.
* {{bor|en|la|accumulātus|withtext=1}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|accumulō||amass, pile up}}, formed from {{m|la|ad||to, towards, at}} + {{m|la|cumulō||heap}}, from {{m|la|cumulus||a heap}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əˈkjuːmjʊˌleɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈkjum.jə.ˌleɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-accumulate.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|accumulat}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[heap]] up in a [[mass]]; to [[pile]] up; to [[collect]] or bring [[together]]; to [[amass]].
#: ''He wishes to '''accumulate''' a sum of money.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[grow]] or [[increase]] in [[quantity]] or [[number]]; to increase [[greatly]].
#* Ill fares the land, to hastening ills a prey, Where wealth '''accumulates''', and men decay. - [[w:Oliver Goldsmith|Oliver Goldsmith]]

